From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 6 <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-28
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: use priv->rx_dma_dev for xsk_pool_dma_map (fix BMan ErrInt)

M3-3 step 6 blocker A residual root cause (spec sec 6.1.5,
"BMan Invalid Command Verb"). After patches 0086 (8-buffer chunked
release) and 0087 (zero bpid bytes before bm_buffer_set64), the BMan
err-IRQ "Invalid Command Verb" (BM_EIRQ_IVCI, bman_ccsr.c:55) still
fires 1:1 with xsk_bman_refill_batches on the DUT G5 reproducer
(verified 2026-05-28 on kernel 6.18.33-vyos commit 34b7c50).

Both prior hypotheses rejected by hardware:
  - 0086: bman_release num>8 BUFCOUNT overflow (chunking applied, still fires)
  - 0087: stack-residue bpid bytes (mainline idiom applied, still fires)

True root cause: DMA device mismatch between the XSK pool map and the
BMan FBPR validation domain.

Mainline dpaa_eth.c probes the RX DMA device from the FMan RX port,
NOT the parent MAC device:

  drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.c:3649
    priv->rx_dma_dev = fman_port_get_device(mac_dev->port[RX]);
    priv->tx_dma_dev = fman_port_get_device(mac_dev->port[TX]);
    err = dma_coerce_mask_and_coherent(priv->rx_dma_dev, DMA_BIT_MASK(40));

Every mainline DMA mapping for buffers that go through BMan uses this
40-bit-mask FMan-port device:

  dpaa_eth.c:1474  dma_map_page(dpaa_bp->priv->rx_dma_dev, ...) [skb path]
  dpaa_eth.c:1631  dma_map_page(dpaa_bp->priv->rx_dma_dev, ...) [bp_add_8_bufs]
  dpaa_eth.c:2888  dma_unmap_page(dpaa_bp->priv->rx_dma_dev, ...) [bp drain]
  dpaa_eth.c:3450  dma_unmap_page(bp->priv->rx_dma_dev, ...)      [bp free]

Our AF_XDP pool DMA-mapped the entire UMEM region against the WRONG
device:

  af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c:192
    xsk_pool_dma_map(pool, priv->mac_dev->dev, DMA_ATTR_SKIP_CPU_SYNC);
                            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
                            parent MAC device, default 32-bit DMA mask,
                            different of_node / iommu group than the
                            FMan port device that owns the BMan FBPR
                            window programmed by U-Boot.

The dma_addr_t values returned by xsk_buff_xdp_get_dma() are therefore
valid IOVAs for the MAC device but BMan validates incoming buffer
addresses against the FBPR window scoped to the FMan port device.
The address resolves outside that window and the BMan rejects the
release verb with IVCI ("Invalid Command Verb"), even though the
verb-byte itself, the bpid, and the buffer count are well-formed.

This explains why both 0086 and 0087 - which addressed only the verb
layout and the bpid bytes - failed to silence the ErrInt: the bytes
in the RCR ring were correct from BMan's perspective; it was the
40-bit address in slot N's hi+lo that was unreachable through the
FBPR window.

Fix: use priv->rx_dma_dev (same device mainline uses for its
dma_map_page() in dpaa_bp_add_8_bufs) as the xsk_pool_dma_map() target.
priv->rx_dma_dev is populated in dpaa_netdev_setup() (dpaa_eth.c:3649),
which runs during dpaa_eth_probe() well before any XSK attach call,
so the field is always non-NULL at xsk_pool_attach time. The added
WARN_ON serves as defense-in-depth if dpaa_netdev_setup() ever changes
ordering relative to xsk_pool_attach.

The DMA_ATTR_SKIP_CPU_SYNC attribute is preserved: the CoreNet fabric
is cache-coherent for the FMan masters on LS1046A so the
per-operation barriers are unnecessary; this matches mainline's
behaviour for the skb-path BP refill (it uses the streaming-DMA
default, which on CoreNet-coherent arm64 is also a no-op for the
sync arms).

The XSK pool detach path will automatically call xsk_pool_dma_unmap()
against the same device (the pool stores the cookie internally), so
no companion change is required in af_xdp_pool_xsk_pool_detach().

Spec ref: M3-3 step 6 blocker A true root cause.
Predecessors: 0086 (verb-count chunking, retained), 0087 (bpid zero, retained).
Verification: DUT G5 (xsk-bind-probe + iperf3 UDP flood);
expected outcomes:
  - `bman_ccsr 1890000.bman: ErrInt: Invalid Command Verb` count -> 0
  - xsk_bman_refill_batches counter continues to increment normally
  - rx_packets=0 will remain until the XSKMAP redirect into
    rx_default_dqrr is wired (separate blocker B, patch 0089+).
Failure-mode if hypothesis wrong: ErrInt count unchanged; next
candidate is enabling CONFIG_FSL_DPAA_CHECKING=y to convert
DPAA_ASSERT into BUG() and extract the failing num+bpid+bufs[0].lo
on the stack.

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
index fa1f50f..9565b46 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -189,7 +189,8 @@ return -ENODEV;
 	 * Failure here is a hard error (misconfigured IOMMU or OOM for the
 	 * DMA-mapping slab).  Do not fall back to copy-mode silently.
 	 */
-	ret = xsk_pool_dma_map(pool, priv->mac_dev->dev,
+	WARN_ON(!priv->rx_dma_dev);
+ret = xsk_pool_dma_map(pool, priv->rx_dma_dev,
 			       DMA_ATTR_SKIP_CPU_SYNC);
 	if (ret) {
 		priv->xsk_dma_map_fail++;
